got a council permit for anything?

555
00:35:31.800 --> 00:35:34.360
- Building consents are
the wider council. not us.

556
00:35:34.360 --> 00:35:38.160
- Right.
- Oh. Hang on. do you mean the tree?

557
00:35:38.160 --> 00:35:40.120
- Tree?
- The big old pohutukawa.

558
00:35:40.120 --> 00:35:42.960
The council gave Gordon permission
to pull it out.

559
00:35:42.960 --> 00:35:44.880
Poppy was not happy about that.

560
00:35:44.880 --> 00:35:48.480
- To pull this tree up. that's
something you'd need a digger for?

561
00:35:48.480 --> 00:35:51.200
- It's a very big one ―
over 20 years old.

562
00:35:51.200 --> 00:35:55.040
Once a native gets to a certain
height. you need a permit.

563
00:35:55.040 --> 00:35:58.760
Look. Gordon perhaps shouldn't
have been allowed to give himself
a permit.

564
00:35:58.760 --> 00:36:02.160
but is a tree worth
stabbing someone for?

565
00:36:02.360 --> 00:36:05.560
- That is a very good
question. Sheree.

566
00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:07.160
- Huh.

567
00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:30.760
- Hey.

568
00:36:30.760 --> 00:36:32.760
So...

569
00:36:33.360 --> 00:36:38.760
Gordon was going to remove a tree.
That's why he had an excavator.

570
00:36:39.240 --> 00:36:41.520
- Do you remember
the first time we met?

571
00:36:41.520 --> 00:36:43.440
Love at first sight.

572
00:36:43.440 --> 00:36:45.440
- Hardly.

573
00:36:45.640 --> 00:36:48.440
You were going out with
what's-her-face. and I was seeing―

574
00:36:48.440 --> 00:36:50.960
- You with that dick
with the '90s goatee.

575
00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:54.400
- Because it was the '90s. Cole.
- Yeah. but still. I knew...

576
00:36:54.400 --> 00:36:58.600
- ...from the second
 knew.

577
00:36:59.320 --> 00:37:02.120
- Hey. Whoa. whoa. whoa.
What's― What's going on?
- I knew.

578
00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:05.160
- Well. we don't have time for that.
- I knew that goatee-faced guy
would not last.

579
00:37:05.160 --> 00:37:08.040
- You're right. He didn't.

580
00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:11.720
- I worked out what the names
you found mean.

581
00:37:11.720 --> 00:37:14.880
Reid. Ryder. Twose. Marshall.

582
00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:18.360
First names ―
John. Jesse. Roger. Hamish.

583
00:37:19.240 --> 00:37:21.600
They're cricketers.
Some of them are kind of obscure.

584
00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:24.400
but they all represented New Zealand
at some point.

585
00:37:24.400 --> 00:37:26.720
- Select and Swig
every Friday night.

586
00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:30.520
- Exactly.
- Oh. honey. you are
a...  genius.

587
00:37:30.520 --> 00:37:33.960
- Exactly.
- Well. I did have to Google it.

588
00:37:33.960 --> 00:37:36.760
- Still. it wasn't about the cats.

589
00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:41.720
- Hey. Hey. I got your text.

590
00:37:41.760 --> 00:37:44.320
- Lincoln. thanks for coming.
This is my wife. Vinnie.

591
00:37:44.320 --> 00:37:47.640
- Good to meet you. Lincoln.
- Likewise. Um. has
something come up?

592
00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:51.680
- Yeah. Yeah.
I just. um. wanted to ask ― why did
you come here on Monday morning?

593
00:37:51.680 --> 00:37:55.040
- Oh. I just. uh. bought him
a coffee. like I sometimes did.

594
00:37:55.040 --> 00:37:58.920
cos I didn't know that he―
- You didn't know he was... dead.

595
00:37:58.920 --> 00:38:00.920
Mm-hm. Yup.
- Yeah.

596
00:38:00.920 --> 00:38:03.480
- Yeah. that's not quite
the genius move you think it is.

597
00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:06.080
- I'm confused. Gordon was my mate.

598
00:38:06.080 --> 00:38:07.720
- Bit dangerous being your mate.

599
00:38:07.720 --> 00:38:10.680
- She needs to watch what
she's saying. your missus.

600
00:38:10.680 --> 00:38:14.960
- Oh. Really?
Well. my 'missus' is right.

601
00:38:14.960 --> 00:38:18.840
You lost your best friend
to a shark attack 20 years ago
where you were the only witness.

602
00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:23.480
- What's that got to do with―
- And then last week. another
friend. another violent death.

603
00:38:23.480 --> 00:38:26.080
- Two dead pals. One common factor.

604
00:38:26.080 --> 00:38:28.360
- It's actually pretty cruel.
what you're saying.

605
00:38:28.360 --> 00:38:31.600
- Well. if 'm gonna be
sorry. But 'm wrong.

606
00:38:31.600 --> 00:38:35.280
- Because you were here
on Friday night. Even though
you said Gordon rain-checked.

607
00:38:35.280 --> 00:38:37.800
- We're gonna start with
what we had for last week.
So we've got Rutherford.

608
00:38:37.800 --> 00:38:38.760
- Yup.

609
00:38:38.760 --> 00:38:40.440
- Your weekly Select and Swig
thing did happen.

610
00:38:40.440 --> 00:38:43.400
- Reid. Ryder. Twose
and Marshall. right?

611
00:38:43.400 --> 00:38:46.400
They were some of the what-if team
you wrote down that night?

612
00:38:46.400 --> 00:38:48.920
- So that's why
you're falsely accusing me?

613
00:38:48.920 --> 00:38:51.640
Cos of a list of cricket players?
- Nope.

614
00:38:51.640 --> 00:38:53.240
Cos of the tree.

615
00:38:53.240 --> 00:38:56.440
- And a shark. who
you falsely accused.

616
00:38:57.160 --> 00:39:00.800
- Your friend didn't run into
a great white that night in 2001.

617
00:39:00.800 --> 00:39:03.920
He ran into something
far more dangerous.

618
00:39:03.920 --> 00:39:10.120
A so-called mate
in love with his girl and willing
to do anything to get her.

619
00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:12.280
You killed Curtis.

620
00:39:12.440 --> 00:39:15.760
Right? You buried him here
at your grandparents' bach.
put a tree on top of him.

621
00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:21.200
- A tree that is now 20-years big.
and blocking Gordon's sea view.

622
00:39:21.200 --> 00:39:25.960
- If he'd dug up that pohutukawa. he
would've found your secret. right?
- But he wouldn't bedeterred.

623
00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:28.080
- Come on. mate. It's a native.
- It's a weed.

624
00:39:28.080 --> 00:39:31.160
- I'm begging you to leave it.
I planted that thing as a tiny shrub.

625
00:39:31.160 --> 00:39:33.600
- And I've got you to blame.

626
00:39:33.600 --> 00:39:37.400
No. it's blocking my view.
Roots everywhere.
- No. you don't get it.

627
00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:40.200
Things could go really bad for me.

628
00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:43.720
I could lose everything.
including Jodie.

629
00:39:43.720 --> 00:39:48.200
- What. you got a body buried
under there or something?

630
00:39:49.680 --> 00:39:51.720
I'll go and get us another beer.

631
00:39:51.720 --> 00:39:56.360
- Maybe you felt like there was
nothing else you could do.

632
00:39:58.360 --> 00:40:00.360
- Hey there.

633
00:40:00.600 --> 00:40:03.760
- Maybe it was easy.
You'd already killed once.

634
00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:04.800
- Ah!

635
00:40:04.800 --> 00:40:08.440
- This is all bullshit speculation.
Grabbing at straws.

636
00:40:08.440 --> 00:40:10.440
Prove it.

637
00:40:10.440 --> 00:40:12.880
- Be good if he wasn't late.
- He's usually quite punctual. I―

638
00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:15.680
- Oh. Wait.

639
00:40:15.680 --> 00:40:18.080
- What's― What's happening?

640
00:40:18.080 --> 00:40:21.960
- We are proving it.

641
00:40:22.320 --> 00:40:25.800
- Kia ora!
- Constable.
these two are on something ―

642
00:40:25.800 --> 00:40:29.360
the rubbish they're talking.
- They think there's a body
under that tree.

643
00:40:29.360 --> 00:40:33.240
Shall we have a look?
- You can't be serious.
- Love at first sight.

644
00:40:33.240 --> 00:40:37.040
You know. when you―
when you said that about your wife.
it got me thinking.

645
00:40:37.040 --> 00:40:39.880
It's a special thing.
when you find your soulmate.

646
00:40:39.880 --> 00:40:42.480
- But yours was with someone else.

647
00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:44.240
Your best mate. Curtis.

648
00:40:44.240 --> 00:40:46.520
- Crack into it. constable.

649
00:40:46.720 --> 00:40:48.720
- No!

650
00:40:50.400 --> 00:40:52.400
Please.

651
00:40:52.680 --> 00:40:54.680
 can't―

652
00:40:55.400 --> 00:40:57.120
I can't break her heart.

653
00:40:57.120 --> 00:40:58.920
What would you do?

654
00:40:58.920 --> 00:41:02.680
For the woman you love. You tell me.
- Well. I'd. um...

655
00:41:02.680 --> 00:41:05.920
I'd wait till she realised
the guy she was with was a...

656
00:41:05.920 --> 00:41:12.400
a goatee-faced dick.
and then I'd make my move
at a friend's divorce barbecue.

657
00:41:13.520 --> 00:41:15.520
- Lincoln Fernsby.

658
00:41:16.560 --> 00:41:22.080
Wouldn't be going anywhere just yet.
Just a tip-off we wanna look into.

659
00:41:26.720 --> 00:41:32.000
- You know. I was only 90% sure
there was a body under that tree.

660
00:41:32.800 --> 00:41:36.120
- Well. you're right
most of the time.
- Most?

661
00:41:36.120 --> 00:41:39.400
Burnsie's divorce party.

662
00:41:39.480 --> 00:41:42.880
It was me who made
the first move. Not you.

663
00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:52.240
- Thanks for your assistance on
this one. constable. Not a bad job.

664
00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:56.280
- Well. you know.
Bit of help from the consultants.

665
00:41:56.280 --> 00:42:00.680
I have been really lucky having
them here. I've learned a lot.

666
00:42:00.680 --> 00:42:04.920
- It's a bit odd though. isn't it?
A couple of small-town motel owners?

667
00:42:04.920 --> 00:42:06.800
- Who used to be police detectives.

668
00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:09.520
- Did you ever ask for
any kind of ID?

669
00:42:09.520 --> 00:42:13.200
- No.
- Any evidence at all that
they're actually police?

670
00:42:13.200 --> 00:42:15.520
- Well. I've had no reason to.

671
00:42:15.520 --> 00:42:19.240
Look ― Vinnie and Cole
know what they're doing.

672
00:42:19.240 --> 00:42:21.240
- The thing is...

673
00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:26.080
I've been in touch with
New South Wales Homicide.

674
00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:38.680
- Your mates.
